commentBody:
@Barry Ancona

I woke up in the middle of the night, reached for my phone to see what time it was, realized the puzzle would have just dropped, and got to solving. It even occurred to me that it’d be a slow solve being that groggy. And… I posted a Wednesday average. 

The fill was interesting but I agree it: This was the wrong day for this puzzle. Unfortunately.

@SP

I thought that cluing ALMODOVAR as a screenwriter rather than as a director was an intentional effort to make the solve a little more difficult (which it accomplished for me).
No complaint; the puzzle needed to be made a little more difficult.

@Saffie
Congratulations!  I have "A 775-DAY STREAK" so far.

I may not do a lot of physical exercise, but I'm definitely getting the brain exercise.

@Saffie

Woohoo! Congratulations!

This puzzle was #901 in my first streak, so I got your back.

@Saffie,

Yay!!! You made it  to 4-digit territory!!

Congratulations!!!🎉🍾🎈

@B

Same with me on Almodovar!  As I am a good speller, this was a welcome correction!

Loved THE FLOWER OF MY SECRET! Have seen few other films by the fine director!

@Mike
You should get a medal for having the mettle to meddle with these folk.

I figured I might as well go for baroque on this one.  I might be a classic, although I might be being overly romantic.

@john ezra
I believe you are mixing up Salma Hayek with Penelope Cruz 
Antonio Banderas also worked with Almodovar.

@john ezra

I constantly mix up Penelope Cruz and Salma Hayek.  

It's really embarrassing when I'm romancing one of them and say the other's name.

@john ezra,

Wow! The way this came out in the thread, after @Francis and @HeathieJ’s comments, it sounded like you were talking about Salma and Penelope. Talk about a player!!

How did this get past those pesky emus?? 😵‍💫

@Sherman

Yes, I was thinking that a bit ago, too!

That would have made a truly wicked clue.

@Andrzej

I don't personally have a nit at the moment, frankly, I'm nitless....  but if I did have a nit, my nit would be better than everyone else's nit. I would be the nittiest!

Get me, I'm nitty!!  🤣

@The X-Phile

There's the cliche that the best standup comics are deeply depressed when not performing.

I've never seen a legit study, but I'd be willing to believe that's true.  I feel my sense of humor peaks when I'm feeling a certain kind of down, a cynical down.  Then again, my preferred mode of humor is dark humor.

@Andrzej

This is starting to grind on me.

I keep repeating, illigitimati non carborundum

@Francis

Exactly my experience.  Boy was it a head banging moment to have to see Ono yet again, when I had convinced myself of the obscure artist Ano.

I hear she eats oreos off the end of an epee.

@Mark Cousins

Mark, that streak is incredible. The fastest times are nowhere near as impressive as that. 

As I sit here on 20 days…

@Grumpy
You are correct that Android app users are treated like red headed step children.

 if you can use a browser on a laptop or desktop,  you should be able to find then.  Or uninstall the app on your phone and access games on a browser, look at what you want, then reinstall app.

@Grumpy
Android app doesn't give access to stats. You can find it while logged into nyt here:

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/puzzles/stats" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/puzzles/stats</a>

@Beth in Greenbelt

Did you miss the (var.)?

Basically, when they NYT wants to misspell something in the crossword, they use the "variant" get-out-of-jail-free card.

@Beth in Greenbelt

That's why he added "var."

That's the joke.

@david dell

I totally agree and you said it better than I have been able to after various attempts.

For all the responders who beg to differ, there is a difference between intellectually stimulating wordplay and unimportant trivia you may or may not happen to know. I'm of the Stones/Led Zeppelin era but it's not an age thing, it's a preference for clues that actually challenge.

@Barry Ancona

Good for you for knowing the restaurant. For somebody who isn't familiar with it, the cross with IvS/INS was impossible to spot as problematic 🤷

In my experience, so many abbreviations (as perceived by me) lacked the "abbr." indication in previous puzzles, I can't possibly remember which it were 🤷

@Andrzej

Idioms and colloquialisms are tough for non-native speakers!

I wonder if Joseph Conrad mastered many in his English-language fiction and non-fiction!

@Wendy P

They are. I picked many up over 4 decades, but i'm still far from native levels of fluency regarding idioms.

Also, I was 30, I think, when I learned to pronounce Arkansas 🙂 (I blame Kansas).

@Mick

It want intentional - you're brilliant for making the connection 🤩

I drop a black tea bag into my Rolling Stones mug, pour over hot water, leave the bag in for waaaay too long by any civilzed standard, and voila. No ceremonies are involved in any of my tea drinking 🤣

@Andrzej

Well, if you pronounced Arkansas as "R-Kansas", you're in good company.

I had never heard it pronounced anything other than (r-CAN-saw), and was stunned when the granddaddy of all news anchors, Walter Cronkite, pronounced it R-Kansas on NBC Nightly News.

@Ιασων

I used to make the same mistake too! 

Now I come after I’ve solved and have tried to predict what people will be complaining about…

@Ιασων, I too tire of the bragging on times. I will say that I achieved a PB, but I never list my time, good or bad! In fact, I don't ever strive to beat my PB; I tend to meander and enjoy the puzzle.

As for difficulty level, I find it to be very subjective, so if I comment upon that, I always qualify it with, "for me". Today, for me, was mostly accessible but I wouldn't call it easy!

Happy solving!

@McX

Yes, when I saw that I had to check the dictionary as I’d not seen the “er” spelling before.  Sad.

Mark

@McX

I was also surprised to see that. If you think the alternate spelling is off, check out the alternate pronunciations. I'm not one to rail against language change, but this is one of those borrowed French words that only sounds right to me with something close to the original pronunciation. It can be risky trying to throw some of these words into conversation if you've mostly only seen them in print. My brother-in-law used this word recently, and his pronunciation made me wonder. I think it was close to one of the M-W versions, but it sounded weird to me. 

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/accoutrement" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/accoutrement</a>

@Beth in Greenbelt

Almodovar? Heavy? Surely not!

🤣

@Beth in Greenbelt
PISH probably wouldn’t be used in the uk, say, in a job interview or in the classroom. 
Yesterday we had ‘knackered’ for tired in Strands. Viewed as vulgar or rude by some. Links to knackers - how to put it politely - men’s bits. Same in US?

@Beth in Greenbelt

I used to be a big fan of ALMODOVAR, and then I started to grow tired of him (around the time that "Volver" came out).

But then I saw "Pain and Glory" and fell back in love with him.  Great movie!

@Sam Lyons
Did you just summarize your dissertation topic?
Wowie Zowie, as we pedestrian Solvers like to say.

@Teresa

One solver's "clutter" is another's gimme, and what's worth knowing to one person is another's trivia.  It depends on your background and interests.

As people say around here, "Your mileage may vary."

@Jerry

Yeah, that's a great comparison.  Better Call Saul, the spinoff, was also magnificent.

I hesitate to say which I like better, because it's be almost like answering the question of which of your kids or grandkids do you like the most.

@CCNY
It's ALEK, but I see that ALEX is taking up space in your noggin and won't allow the name to be over-written!
(I relied on the crosses.)

@Joe

Yeah, me, too.  I thought I was really chugging away towards becoming a top solver.

It didn't take long for that notion to be squashed.

@Miriam

Your explanation for INS makes the most sense of those I've seen. "Audio In" and "Video In", for example,  would be INS.

My own feeling---dripping with the bitterness of one who has fallen victim to it---is that 35A is a rare example in the NYT of *cruciverbal entrapment*. Indeed, I contend that the clue for INS was intentionally set as "Hookups" simply to ruin the days of those of us who are completely ignorant of chain restaurants that feature "onion volcanoes".

@Barry Ancona

And you also remembered that IVS is always clued with an abbreviation. 

So you solved this one and I didn't. Thanks for supplying lemon juice for my paper cut. ;-)

@Annie

It's strange how Lord of the Rings, keep drawing one back, isn't it.  

I've read it three times, as well.

@Jack McCullough

We also had a reference to the SOLAR ECLIPSE with the column photo just two days ago. Unfortunately, IMO, because it made that answer jump out a little too easily!

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2025/07/08/crosswords/daily-puzzle-2025-07-09.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2025/07/08/crosswords/daily-puzzle-2025-07-09.html</a>

@Dan Woog. Three would certainly have been correct too.  But I think that because two is smaller than three, the clue with two works also.

Had the actor been named Harrison Adams, I guess, well, one, two, three, or four presidents could work.

I once knew someone named Ruth Ruth, her married name.  I’m not sure how someone named Harrison Harrison would have been clued.

@sonnel

Two is only smaller than three for small values of two.

(That's a math joke for you and Andrzej.)

@Xword Junkie
Aha! Hook-up here is akin to connections. Thus, "I'd love some tickets to Wimbledon. Can you hook me up?" I.e., "can you put me in touch / make a connection for me with a insider?"
Hope this is clearer.

@Lewis

Ah, of course.  I also subscribe to xwordinfo but have not delved into the grid design db.  I've only used it for clue/answer lookups.  Many thanks.

Oh, and I'm sure your memory is way above average!

@JohnWM

I have zero experience with this but it's the first Startpage.com search hit, maybe worth a look.

<a href="https://games.washingtonpost.com/games/hard-crossword" target="_blank">https://games.washingtonpost.com/games/hard-crossword</a>

@Byron

Thanks for the somewhat strange lesson in logical reasoning.  I taught logic for a number of years, so I don't know whether I needed it.  You'll note that I didn't make any of the inferences you refer to.  Indeed, I didn't make any inferences at all.

Julien Francis won the 100m dash in Paris in 2024.  She is the one and only Olympic medalist from her home country of Saint Lucia.  What inferences do you think we can make from that?

@Mean Old Lady 

I amazed myself by managing to get ROAR from one letter (the "O") and the clue. It made me mentally strut around for a while. Still doing that, actually.

I did have to google a few things, though.

@Jerry 

The puzzles tend to favor older solvers anyway, if for no other reason than being older means more years to accumulate trivial knowledge. There's a conscious effort to correct for that, and there should be. 

I remind myself of that every time I can easily answer a clue about, say, some 1960s sitcom. Having to answer clues about current slang, music, internet memes, whatever, is just the price you pay for that edge.

@Barry Ancona

If you don't have a yard, then what do you mow?  Do you go to a nearby park to mow?

Isn't mowing a lawn something every single person on earth has to do?

@SBK

Unfortunately, when I try to read Asimov's fiction these days, I find his characters one-dimensional and prone to histrionics.  

But I bet his science fact writings, though dates, are probably still terrific.

@Andrzej, you might pick up some mathematics through Asimov's writings about math history 😀.

@Francis

There are other issues to hold against him, unfortunately.  :(

(Unrepentant groper.)

@Andrzej

Ah, c'mon.  Through Asimov, I knew the number google long, long before it became Google.

As I recall, he didn't like the name google, saying it sounded like a child's word.  And it was!

@Michael B.

I had just lined it up on Spotify before coming here! If this review is anything to go by, it should be good.

<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2025/jul/10/clipse-let-god-sort-em-out-review" target="_blank">https://www.theguardian.com/music/2025/jul/10/clipse-let-god-sort-em-out-review</a>

@Andrzej

And, once again, you were sure of the very person I was totally clueless about.

Like you said, it's almost like we didn't have exactly the same experiences after all.  Don't know why that would be.  😀

@Tim

I never did.  I gave up with the only mistake being aNO.

I really hate vowels.  wsh w ddn't hv vwls.

@N

It must be tough being as perfect as you are.  Just one mistake would justifiably cause you to lose your job, and you would no longer have any worth as an individual.  Your friends and family would likely abandon you.

Such pressure to live under!

@N

Wow, high bar for a crossword chat board commentator. 

Sure, “host” has a broader meaning than just troops but it does have that meaning so all fair.

@N

If everybody was who didn't know everything was fired, no one would have a job and nothing would ever get done.

Try being a human being.  You might like it.

@Endall
I'm not sure about "exponential" change in difficulty.
But while I'd agree that this one was on the easier side of Friday puzzles, the average difficulty of Friday puzzles doesn't seem to have changed much in my view. At least over the last 10 years. We can all cherrypick certain Fridays to make a point but that's why I like referring to the averages in archives if we're looking for trends.

